Next you‚Äôll add shelf-stable gnocchi, which boils directly in the sauce. Top with the seared chicken and a generous amount of cheese and stick it under the broiler until browned and bubbling. This recipe works best with the shelf-stable varieties found near the dried pasta. These are less likely to go gummy and are ideal for cooking directly in the sauce; no boiling required. ffgPVr social-icons social-icons--circular RecipePageSocialIcons-ciwKfN hvKZhf" data-testid="social-icons"><ul data-testid="socialIconslist" class="SocialIconsList-cHVTIA ivmbkv social-icons__list"></ul></div><div class="BodyWrapper-kufPGa iCdXMP body recipe-body" data-journey-hook="client-content" data-testid="BodyWrapper"><div><div class="container container--body"><div class="container--body-inner"><p>Classic <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/ba-syn-bas-best-chicken-parm">chicken parm</a> is hardly <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/recipes-menus/easy-weeknight-dinners">weeknight-friendly</a>. Between breading the chicken, making a slow-simmered sauce, and assembling it all, it requires many steps yet still doesn‚Äôt feel like a complete meal on its own. A near-obligatory side of pasta requires a separate pot of water.</p><p>This version ditches the breading in favor of a generous dusting of flour that still creates browned and crispy edges, and calls for quick-cooking gnocchi that goes in the same pan as the chicken. The key to making this a <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/recipes-menus/our-favorite-one-pot-dinners-gallery">one-skillet meal</a> is to add the ingredients in stages: First you‚Äôll sear your <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/recipes-menus/chicken-breast-recipes">chicken breasts</a>, then make a simple sauce in the same pan. Next you‚Äôll add <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/ingredients/how-shelf-stable-gnocchi-became-a-dinner-hero">shelf-stable gnocchi</a>, which boils directly in the sauce. Top with the seared chicken and a generous amount of cheese and stick it under the broiler until browned and bubbling. Right before serving, shower it with fresh basil and dinner is done: It‚Äôs everything you love about chicken Parmesan in a quicker, fuss-free package.</p><p>A tip about using store-bought gnocchi: While you might be tempted to purchase fresh gnocchi from the refrigerated section of the grocery store, don‚Äôt. This recipe works best with the shelf-stable varieties found near the dried pasta. These are less likely to go gummy and are ideal for cooking directly in the sauce; no boiling required. Fresh gnocchi, by contrast, tends to be much softer and is more apt to turn mushy when cooked.</p></div></div></div></div><div class="TextBlockWrapper-bNZsMC fMUEKc StyledTextblock-SJflO eYjtWF disclaimer"><p class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ TextBlockText-gtrMkY iUEiRd ejxONG kQegaj">All products featured on Epicurious are independently selected by our editors. However, when you buy something through our retail links, we may earn an affiliate commission.</p></div><section class="CarouselWrapper-hZPzMO hslYFL RecipePageCarousel-kfmrKy iTgzgF"><header skinless, boneless chicken breasts (about 1 lb.), patted dry</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">4¬º tsp. Diamond Crystal or 2¬Ω tsp. Morton kosher salt, divided</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">¬º cup all-purpose flour</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">¬º cup (or more) extra-virgin olive oil</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">8 garlic cloves, finely chopped</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">¬Ω tsp. crushed red pepper flakes</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">1 28-oz. can whole peeled tomatoes</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">1¬Ω tsp. sugar</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">1 17.5-oz. package shelf-stable potato gnocchi</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">2 oz. Parmesan, finely grated</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">8 oz. part-skim mozzarella, sliced ¬º&quot; thick</div><div class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ Description-cSrMCf iUEiRd bGCtOd fsKnGI">Basil leaves (for serving; optional)</div></div></div></div><div class="GridItem-buujkM eHLzLy grid--item grid_content_columnTwo"><div><div class="InstructionsWrapper-hZXqPx RmryN" data-testid="InstructionsWrapper"><h2 class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ InstructionListHed-dYZnS iUEiRd fGedxb GZXOQ">Preparation</h2><ol class="InstructionGroupWrapper-bqiIwp ccobUj"><li class="InstructionListWrapper-dcpygI bQnYVe"><h4 class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ InstructionHed-cTDCYA InstructionHedSmall-kvDvLP iwCByY gGkodH ssMUV">Step 1</h4><p>Working with 1 breast at a time, hold a long knife parallel to cutting board and cut <strong>2 medium skinless, boneless chicken breasts (about 1 lb.), patted dry</strong>, in half, slicing along a long side to make thin cutlets. Arrange all 4 cutlets in an even layer on cutting board and sprinkle all over with <strong>2 tsp. Diamond Crystal or 1¬º tsp. Morton kosher salt</strong>. Transfer to a medium bowl and sprinkle with <strong>¬º cup all-purpose flour</strong>; toss to coat.</p><h4 class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ InstructionHed-cTDCYA InstructionHedSmall-kvDvLP iwCByY gGkodH ssMUV">Step 2</h4><p>Heat <strong>¬º cup extra-virgin olive oil</strong> in a large high-sided ovenproof skillet, preferably cast iron, over medium. Working in 2 batches and adding more oil between batches if needed, lift cutlets from bowl, shaking off excess flour, and carefully lower into skillet. Cook until deep golden brown, about 3 minutes per side (chicken will finish cooking in oven). Transfer to a large plate or baking sheet.</p><h4 class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ InstructionHed-cTDCYA InstructionHedSmall-kvDvLP iwCByY gGkodH ssMUV">Step 3</h4><p>Reduce heat to medium-low. Add <strong>8 garlic cloves, finely chopped</strong>, and <strong>¬Ω tsp. crushed red pepper flakes</strong> to skillet and cook, stirring constantly, until fragrant, about 1 minute. Add <strong>one 28-oz. can whole peeled tomatoes</strong>, crushing with your hands as you go, then add remaining <strong>2¬º tsp. Diamond Crystal or 1¬º tsp. Morton kosher salt</strong> and <strong>1¬Ω tsp. sugar</strong>. Bring to a simmer and cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce is slightly thickened, about 5 minutes. Add <strong>one 17.5-oz. package shelf-stable potato gnocchi</strong> and cook, stirring constantly, until gnocchi is barely tender, about 2 minutes. Remove from heat.</p><h4 class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ InstructionHed-cTDCYA InstructionHedSmall-kvDvLP iwCByY gGkodH ssMUV">Step 4</h4><p>Heat broiler. Arrange chicken in a single layer over gnocchi. Top chicken with <strong>2 oz. Parmesan, finely grated</strong>, followed by <strong>8 oz. part-skim mozzarella, sliced ¬º</strong>&quot; <strong>thick</strong>. Transfer skillet to oven and broil until cheese is melted and browned, 5‚Äì8 minutes; watch closely to avoid burning.</p><h4 class="BaseWrap-sc-gjQpdd BaseText-ewhhUZ InstructionHed-cTDCYA InstructionHedSmall-kvDvLP iwCByY gGkodH ssMUV">Step 5</h4><p>Serve chicken parm topped with <strong>basil leaves</strong> if desired.</p></li></ol></div><div class="ActionBarWrapperContent-lasBkU ippmmU"><div class="ActionBarWrapperComponent-cjwxLS bEeSLb"><div data-attr-viewport-monitor="" class="ActionBarWrapper-dhxmQh hBOoqK viewport-monitor-anchor"><button id="bookmark" aria-label="Save" Between breading the chicken, making a slow-simmered sauce, and assembling it all, it requires many steps yet still doesn‚Äôt feel like a complete meal on its own. A near-obligatory side of pasta requires a separate pot of water.\nThis version ditches the breading in favor of a generous dusting of flour that still creates browned and crispy edges, and calls for quick-cooking gnocchi that goes in the same pan as the chicken. The key to making this a one-skillet meal is to add the ingredients in stages: First you‚Äôll sear your chicken breasts, then make a simple sauce in the same pan. Next you‚Äôll add shelf-stable gnocchi, which boils directly in the sauce. Top with the seared chicken and a generous amount of cheese and stick it under the broiler until browned and bubbling. Right before serving, shower it with fresh basil and dinner is done: It‚Äôs everything you love about chicken Parmesan in a quicker, fuss-free package.\nA tip about using store-bought gnocchi: While you might be tempted to purchase fresh gnocchi from the refrigerated section of the grocery store, don‚Äôt. This recipe works best with the shelf-stable varieties found near the dried pasta. These are less likely to go gummy and are ideal for cooking directly in the sauce; no boiling required. Fresh gnocchi, by contrast, tends to be much softer and is more apt to turn mushy when cooked.","alternativeHeadline":"This easy one-pan dinner puts quick-cooking store-bought gnocchi right in the pan
